## 8. ALTER Script Rules

1. **UC naming**: Use the fully-qualified name (`catalog.schema.table`) resolved by the UC Object Resolution algorithm above. **Never infer from Synapse naming conventions.** Every ALTER statement must use the validated 3-level name
2. **Table comment**: Compress the one-line description + key business context from Section 1 into ≤1024 chars. Include: what it is, source, refresh, and the most critical gotchas. **Label Synapse-specific metadata with `Synapse:` prefix** (e.g., `Synapse: HASH(PositionID), CLUSTERED INDEX`) and **UC-specific metadata with `UC:` prefix** (e.g., `UC: Delta, partitioned by etr_y/etr_ym/etr_ymd`). Never leave distribution/index/partitioning unlabeled — readers in UC must not assume Synapse metadata applies to their environment
3. **Column comments**: Compress each element description from Section 4 into ≤1024 chars. Prioritize:
   - Business meaning (what the column represents)
   - FK references (what table to JOIN for resolution)
   - Key values/enums (most important mappings)
   - Gotchas (common misunderstandings)
4. **KEEP tier tags**: Preserve tier suffixes in column comments. These provide traceability — anyone reading a UC column comment can see whether the description came from the upstream wiki (Tier 1), SP code (Tier 2), live data (Tier 3), inference (Tier 4), or domain expert (Tier 5). **Wiki `.md` (Phase 11)** uses the Unicode em dash in prose: `(Tier N — source)` per the template. **All generated SQL** (`.alter.sql`, `.downstream.alter.sql`, `_downstream_column_comments.sql`, and any aggregated COMMENT script) MUST use **ASCII** for the tier delimiter after sanitization: `(Tier N - source)` — never emit raw `—`, `→`, `↔`, `≤`, or `§` inside SQL string literals. **Mandatory**: pass every description through `knowledge/synapse/Wiki/_uc_comment_sanitize.py` (`sanitize_uc_sql_comment_text` or `escape_sql_comment_value`) before `ALTER COLUMN ... COMMENT` / `COMMENT ON COLUMN` / `TBLPROPERTIES`. This fixes CP1255 mojibake (e.g. `ג€"` instead of em dash) and prevents re-corruption on Windows editors. If the description is near the 1024-char limit, the tier tag takes priority over truncating description content
5. **KEEP [UNVERIFIED] tags**: Preserve `[UNVERIFIED]` prefixes on Tier 4 descriptions in the ALTER script. This signals to analysts and the AI assistant that the description is inferred, not confirmed. Unverified items are ALSO tracked in the review sidecar, but the tag in the ALTER output ensures visibility even after deployment to UC
6. **Preserve `Same meaning as Dim_Position.*`** references — these help the AI assistant cross-reference
7. **Single quotes in values**: Escape any single quotes in descriptions with `''` (SQL standard)
8. **One ALTER per column**: Each column gets its own `ALTER TABLE ... ALTER COLUMN ... COMMENT` statement on a single line
9. **ALWAYS backtick-quote column names**: Every `ALTER COLUMN` statement MUST wrap the column name in backticks: `` ALTER COLUMN `ColumnName` COMMENT '...' ``. This is mandatory because Synapse columns may start with digits (`2FA`), contain hyphens (`BNY-eToro_Units`), slashes (`Buy/Sell`), percent signs (`UnitsNOP+1%`), or other special characters that are valid in Synapse but cause syntax errors in Databricks SQL without quoting. Backtick-quoting standard alphanumeric names is harmless; omitting them on special names causes runtime failures
10. **Column name validation**: When UC is available, verify each column exists in the target table before generating its ALTER COLUMN statement. Use `DESCRIBE TABLE {uc_catalog}.{uc_schema}.{uc_table}` to get the actual column list. Skip columns that don't exist in UC (they may have been dropped or renamed) and note them in the review sidecar
11. **UC-only columns**: If `DESCRIBE TABLE` reveals columns that exist in UC but not in Synapse (e.g., partition columns like `etr_y`, `etr_ym`, `etr_ymd`), generate `ALTER COLUMN ... COMMENT` statements for them with a description noting they are Databricks-layer additions (e.g., partition pruning columns)
12. **Single-line executable ALTER**: Each `ALTER TABLE ... ALTER COLUMN ... COMMENT` statement MUST be one physical line with the keyword `COMMENT` intact (no accidental line breaks inside `COMMENT`). Validate with `python tools/fix_uc_sql_mojibake.py --check` after bulk generation.
13. **UTF-8 file encoding on ALL writes (HARD RULE — 2026-03-30)**: Every file write (`.alter.sql`, `.md`, `.review-needed.md`, `.lineage.md`) MUST use explicit `encoding="utf-8"` in Python `open()` calls. Never rely on system default encoding (Windows CP1252/CP1255 corrupts tier tags). The sanitizer is a safety net, not a substitute for writing UTF-8 from the start.
14. **Name-level ALTER-wiki parity (HARD — 2026-03-30)**: Count-only matching is NOT sufficient. Every ALTER COLUMN name (after stripping backticks and lowercasing) must match a wiki Element Name (lowercased), and vice versa. Run `python tools/audit_wiki_alter_comment_parity.py` on the generated `.alter.sql` to validate both column name parity and description text parity.

